erkshire, England, United Kingdom","West Yorkshire, England":"West Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","Devon, England":"Devon, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"McKay","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish and northern Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Aoidh</b> ‘son of <i>Aodh</i>’, an old personal name meaning ‘fire’. Etymologically, this is the same name as   McKee  ,   McGee  ,   McCoy  , and   McHugh  .","History: This is the surname of several Irish and Scottish families, including Clan Mackay, a Highland clan traditionally associated with Sutherland in the far northwest of Scotland."],"variants":[{"name":"McKeegan","meanings":["Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Aodhagáin</b> ‘son of <i>Aodhagán</i>’, a pet form of the ancient Irish personal name <i>Aodh</i> ‘fire’ (see   McKay  ). <b>Mac Aodhagáin</b> was a learned family in Connacht. See also   Keegan  ."]},{"name":"Mackey","meanings":["Pronounced with the stress on the first syllable, this is Irish, an Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Macdha</b> ‘descendant of <i>Macdha</i>’, a personal name meaning ‘virile, manly’.","With the stress on the second syllable, it is a variant of Scottish and Irish   McKay  ."]},{"name":"Quay","meanings":["Scottish and Irish: shortened form of   McKay   or   McKee  .","English: variant of   Kay  .","French: topographic name for someone who lived in a house on a quayside, from Old French <i>quai</i> ‘quay’."]},{"name":"McKee","meanings":["Irish (northern): Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Aodha</b> or <b>Mac Aoidh</b> ‘son of <i>Aodh</i>’, an old personal name meaning ‘fire’. Thus, this name has the same origin as   McKay  ,   McGee  ,   McCoy  , and   McHugh  ."]},{"name":"Mackay","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   McKay  ."]},{"name":"McHugh","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Conal, Sinead, Brigid, Conall, Cormac, Eamon, Eamonn, Fintan, Kieran, Malachy, Patrick Sean.","Irish and Scottish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Aodha</b> or <b>Mac Aoidh</b> ‘son of <i>Aodh</i>’, an old personal name meaning ‘fire’, originally the name of a pagan god. Thus the name has the same origin as   McKay  ,   McGee  , and   McCoy  . See also   Hughes   3."]}]},{"name":"Helen","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["vernacular form of the name (Greek <i>Hēlēnē</i>) borne in classical legend by a famous beauty, wife of Menelaus, whose seizure by the Trojan prince Paris sparked off the Trojan War. Her name is of uncertain origin; it may be connected with a word meaning ‘ray’ or ‘sunbeam’ compare Greek <i>hēlios</i> ‘sun’. It has sometimes been taken as connected with the Greek word meaning ‘Greek’, <i>Hellēn</i>, but this is doubtful. In the early Christian period the name was borne by the mother of the Emperor Constantine, who is now usually known by the Latin version of her name, <i>Helena</i>. She is credited with having found the True Cross in Jerusalem. She was born in about  248 , probably in Bithynia. However, in medieval England it was believed that she had been born in Britain, which greatly increased the popularity of the name there."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Helen McKay was born in 1566, in West Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom as the daughter of Iye Du Mackay. She had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Michael Thome Smithe. She died in 1610, in her hometown, at the age of 44."},"et":{"1566–1610":"1566–1610","1565–1610":"1565–1610","1588–Male":"1588–Surnud","1596–1644":"1596–1644","1508–1572":"1508–1572","1644":"1644","1566":"1566","08 SEP 1588":"8. september 1588","1610":"1610","1588":"1588","1565":"1565","1596":"1596","1572":"1572","1508":"1508","18 October 1596":"18. oktoober 1596","Chieveley,Berkshire,England":"Chieveley, Berkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","West Yorkshire, England":"West Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United King